"Rude Boy" was released as the third US and second international single from Rihanna's fourth studio album, ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cochrane|first=Greg|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/10002471|title=Rihanna track gets worldwide premiere|work=''[[BBC News]]''|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2009-10-20|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref><ref name="MTV Rated R appearance">{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/12/11/spotted-rihannas-makes-a-rated-r-apperance-on-german-tv/|title=Spotted: Rihanna's Makes A 'Rated R' Appearance On German TV|work=''[[MTV]]''|publisher=[[Viacom]]|date=2009-12-11|accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Marcell|last=Minaya|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a183504/rihannas-next-single-announced.html|title=Rihanna's next single announced?|work=''[[Digital Spy]]''|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias|Hachette Filipacchi (UK) Ltd]]|date=2009-10-24|accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> and was solicited to [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio stations on February 9, 2010 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/singlesreviews/|title=Singles Release Diary|work=''[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi UK|date=2010-03-18|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The song was made available to purchase as a CD single on February 19, 2010 in Ireland<ref name="Ireland Release">{{cite web|last=Cuffe|first=Aidan|url=http://www.goldenplec.com/2010/01/20/rhianna-announces-second-o2-date/|title=Rhianna announces second O2 date|publisher=Golden Plec|date=2010-01-20|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> and was released worldwide via digital download on February 22, 2010.<ref name="US Release">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/au/album/rude-boy-single/id353493307|title=Rude Boy - Single|work=''[[iTunes Store]] (US)''|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|date=2010-02-19|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> "Rude Boy" was co-written by Rihanna, [[Mikkel S. Eriksen]], [[Tor Erik Hermansen]], [[Ester Dean]], [[Makeba Riddick]], [[Rob Swire]], with production completed by Eriksen and Hermansen (under their production name [[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]) and Swire.<ref name="About.com">{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/rihannarudeboy.htm|title=Rihanna - Rude Boy - Review of Rude Boy Single By Rihanna - About.com|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The song is an [[up-tempo]] dance song and incorporates a multitude of various musical genres, drawing heavily on [[dancehall]] and [[ragga|ragamuffin]]<ref name="Nick Levine">{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a203939/rihanna-rude-boy.html|title=Rihanna: 'Rude Boy'|work=''Digital Spy''|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi UK|date=2010-03-18|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref><ref name="Powers">{{cite news|last=Powers|first=Ann|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/11/album-review-rihannas-rated-r.html|title=Album review: Rihanna's 'Rated R'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=2009-11-23|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> as well as [[pop music|pop]]  and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name="Musicnotes">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdVPE.asp?ppn=MN0083266|title=Rude Boy - Rihanna Digital Music Sheet|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]|productnumber=MN0083266 (Product Number)|year=2009|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> and is written in the key of [[E-flat minor]] with a [[time signature]] in [[common time]], and a [[tempo]] of 96 beats per minute.<ref name="Musicnotes"/> Nick Levine of [[Digital Spy]] commented that "'Rude Boy' can be construed as a winning synthesis of her Island-pop beginnings" and that it is "the raciest she's ever been, instructing the titular brute to "give it to me baby like boom boom boom", promising to "turn his body out" and repeatedly inquiring as to whether he's 'big enough.'"<ref name="Nick Levine"/>

==Critical reception==
"Rude Boy" was met with generally positively by music critics. Alexis Petridis of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that "Rude Boy", along with the albums previous single "[[Hard (song)|Hard]]", was one of the highlights of ''Rated R'', saying "both of which exploit Rihanna's most appealing vocal style, a sulky, icy, monotone."<ref name="Petridis">{{cite news|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/nov/19/rihanna-cd-review|title=Rihanna: Rated R|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=2009-11-19|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} reviewer [[Ann Powers]] stated that the song has a  "[[ragga|ragamuffin]]-style", as well as commenting on the lyrics of the song, stating "Even as she offers herself in no uncertain terms -- "I'm gon' let you be the captain tonight," she sneers -- she questions his prowess. "Can you get it up? Are you big enough?" she repeats in the singsong chorus, making it tough to imagine that any suitor could rise to this occasion."<ref name="Powers"/> Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] praised the song, calling it "the most instantly engaging song from the album Rated R", and that "[Rihanna] projects a dominant female image that is exactly what was needed to move past the unfortunate [[Chris Brown (American singer)|Chris Brown]] chapter in her career".<ref name="About.com"/> However, Lamb added that the "icy feel is wearing thin. Rihanna sounds like she has taken a few steps back to distance herself from the whole song. There is a pleasing swagger, but we're never quite engaged".<ref name="About.com"/> The reviewer for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' wrote, "with 'Rude Boy', Rihanna delivers her most provocative lyrics and perhaps most authentic-sounding single to date. The singer makes good use of the song's title <U+2013> an old Jamaican slang term for lawless males <U+2013> and relishes her role as antagonist. [[Steel drum]]s are a welcome presence on the production, which gives a nod to [[ska]] and [[dancehall]]. Rihanna's swagger has never been as convincing as on this song, and thanks to an accompanying video that pays tribute to [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.'s]] global pop culture references, 'Rude Boy' is poised for success."<ref name="Reuters">{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE61P5PO20100226|title=Billboard singles reviews: Rihanna, Ke$ha|work=''[[Reuters]]''|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|date=2010-02-26|accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref> Nick Levine also reviewed the song positively, writing, "On the one hand, 'Rude Boy' can be construed as a winning synthesis of her Island-pop beginnings, the effortless hitmaking of the ''Good Girl Gone Bad'' era and the more menacing persona she's unveiled post-Grammygate. On the other, it's just a damn good tune...it's the most instantly catchy moment from her ''Rated R'' album, a dancehall-inflected delight that takes all of ten seconds to get to the hook."<ref name="Nick Levine"/>

==Chart performance==
In the [[United States]], "Rude Boy" debuted on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number sixty-four,<ref>{{cite web|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/ke-ha-stops-world-from-spinning-a-no-1-on-1004068721.story#/news/ke-ha-stops-world-from-spinning-a-no-1-on-1004068721.story|title=Ke$ha Stops 'World' From Spinning A No. 1 On Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|date=2010-02-18|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> and peaked at number one a month later, replacing "[[Break Your Heart]]" by [[Taio Cruz]]. The song become Rihanna's sixth number-one on the chart,<ref>{{cite web|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/rihanna-rules-hot-100-with-rude-boy-track-1004076296.story#/news/rihanna-rules-hot-100-with-rude-boy-track-1004076296.story|title=Rihanna Rules Hot 100 With 'Rude Boy' Track|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-03-17|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> tying her with [[Paula Abdul]] and [[Diana Ross]] for having the fifth-most number ones among female artists within the Hot 100's in its fifty-one year history.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/column/chartbeat/chart-beat-thursday-rihanna-ludacris-timbaland-1004076867.story|title=Chart Beat Thursday: Rihanna, Ludacris, Timbaland|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-03-18|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> The song remained at the number-one position for consecutive five weeks,<ref>{{cite web|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/rihanna-refuses-to-budge-from-hot-100-perch-1004083542.story#/news/rihanna-refuses-to-budge-from-hot-100-perch-1004083542.story|title=Rihanna Refuses to Budge from Hot 100 Perch|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-04-15|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> before being replaced by "[[Nothin' On You]]" by [[B.o.B]] featuring [[Bruno Mars]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/b-o-b-weaves-way-to-hot-100-no-1-glee-generates-1004085701.story#/news/b-o-b-weaves-way-to-hot-100-no-1-glee-generates-1004085701.story|title=B.o.B Weaves Way To Hot 100 No. 1; 'Glee' Generates More Debuts|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-04-22|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> "Rude Boy" also topped the US [[Hot Dance Airplay]], [[Rhythmic Airplay Chart|Rhythmic Airplay]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/column-chartbeat/chart-beat-wednesday-top-40-meets-buble-1004084587.story#/column-chartbeat/chart-beat-wednesday-top-40-meets-buble-1004084587.story|title=Chart Beat Wednesday: Top 40 Meets Buble|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-04-21|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/column-chartbeat/chart-beat-wednesday-diva-domination-1004087021.story#/column-chartbeat/chart-beat-wednesday-diva-domination-1004087021.story |title=Chart Beat Wednesday: Diva Domination|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-04-28|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> and [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Dance/Club Play Songs]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/dance-club-play-songs?chartDate=2010-05-15#/charts/dance-club-play-songs?chartDate=2010-05-15|title=Dance/Club Play Songs|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|date=2010-05-15|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> The song was also certified 2x Platinum denoting sales of over two million copies.{{certification Cite Ref|title=Rude Boy|type=single|artist=Rihanna|region=United States}} On February 21, 2010, "Rude Boy" debuted atop the [[UK R&B Chart]],<ref name="UKRandBchart"/> and peaked at number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]], being barred by [[Tinie Tempah|Tinie Tempah's]] "[[Pass Out (Tinie Tempah song)|Pass Out]]", which debuted at number one and held the top spot for two weeks.<ref name="UKchart"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2010-03-20|title=Archive Chart|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> On April 30, the single was certified Gold for selling 400,000 copies.{{certification Cite Ref|title=Rude Boy|type=single|artist=Rihanna|region=United Kingdom}} "Rude Boy" debuted on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]] at number forty-five, peaking at number one for two weeks in mid-March.<ref name="AUSchart"/> It remained on the chart for nineteen weeks, and certified 2x Platinum denoting sales of over 140,000 copies.{{certification Cite Ref|title=Rude Boy|type=single|artist=Rihanna|region=Australia|certyear=2010}}

==Music video==
===Background===
[[File:Rihanna rudeboy.jpg|thumb|right|Rihanna wearing a gold net bodysuit in the video.]]
The [[music video]] for "Rude Boy" was directed by [[Melina Matsoukas]],<ref name="M.I.A">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/25/rihannas-rude-boy-video-director-responds-to-criticism/|title=Rihanna's 'Rude Boy' video director responds to criticism|work=[[Rap-Up]]|publisher=Devin Lazerine|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> who also directed the video for Rihanna's previous single, "[[Hard (song)|Hard]]",<ref name="Herrera">{{cite web|last=Herrera|first=Monica|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/rihanna-sizzles-in-new-rude-boy-music-video-1004067020.story#/news/rihanna-sizzles-in-new-rude-boy-music-video-1004067020.story|title=Rihanna Sizzles In New 'Rude Boy' Music Video|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielssn Media|date=2010-02-11|accessdate=2010-11-22}}</ref> and was shot in January 2010 in [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California]]. All of the video relied heavily on the use of [[greenscreen]], and contained strong references to critically acclaimed famous artists, including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Keith Haring]] and [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]].<ref name="Herrera"/><ref name="truecolors">{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1631691/20100211/rihanna.jhtml|title=Rihanna Shows Her True Colors In 'Rude Boy' Video|work=''[[MTV]]''|publisher=[[Viacom]]|date=2010-02-11|accessdate=2010-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/18/video-on-set-of-rihannas-rude-boy/#more-39475|title=Video: On Set of Rihanna<U+2019>s <U+2018>Rude Boy<U+2019>|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-02-18|accessdate=2010-03-18}}</ref> In an interview with Carson Daly on his radio show, Amp Radio, Rihanna described the video as "completely different from any other video" she had done before and "pretty freakin' cool", as well as explaining its artistic qualities, saying "A lot of my videos are really dark and edgy and tough. 'Rude Boy' is more playing along the lines from my roots. We used a lot of color, but also the costumes were very Jamaican dance-hall-queen type."<ref name="truecolors"/> The video premiered on February 10, 2010 via the high definition music video provider [[VEVO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/08/on-set-of-rihannas-rude-boy-video/|title=On Set of Rihanna<U+2019>s 'Rude Boy<U+2019> Video|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|accessdate=2010-03-18}}</ref>

===Synopsis===
The video features Rihanna in a multitude of different brightly colored and vibrant Caribbean inspired scenes<ref name="Videopreview">{{cite web|last=Barnes|first=Marcus|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1249598/Rihanna-goes-roots-new-Caribbean-themed-music-video-single-Rude-Boy.html#ixzz1UZTMExhO|title=Rihanna goes back to her roots with Caribbean-themed new video for Rude Boy|work=[[Mail Online]]|publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]]|date=2010-02-09|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The video starts with Rihanna walking up to a drum kit, which she continues to play throughout as the song starts to develop. Throughout the rest of the video, Rihanna is seen engaging and playing with a variety of different props, including a male extra, a zebra, a motorcycle and a stuffed lion, which are intercut with scenes of Rihanna continuing to play the drum kit.<ref name="truecolors"/> There are also numerous different outfits which Rihanna adorns throughout the video, including a gold net bodysuit and a black and white zebra print catsuit, which she wears whilst sitting on top of a stuffed zebra.<ref name="Videopreview"/> As well as numerous costumes, Rihanna also incorporates various 90s dancehall dance moves such as the [[Gerald Levy|Bogle]], the butterfly, and the tatti.

===Reception===
Upon the videos release, several media outlets noticed a resemblance between the colorful aesthetics of "Rude Boy" and British singer-songwriter and rapper [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.]]'s video  "[[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]".<ref name="M.I.A"/> Director Melina Matsoukas responded to the allegations that she had copied the idea, saying "Afterward I was like, <U+2018>Oh, this sucks. They tore down my video &nbsp;....&nbsp; [M.I.A.'s] video<U+2019>s great too. It definitely wasn<U+2019>t trying to rip anybody off at all, it was just our approach and the animation stuff, it had a similar vibe." Matsoukas went on to explain that the inspiration for the treatment of the video did not come from one particular source and comes from a variety of different pop culture icons, and concluded that "We<U+2019>re all inspired by similar elements and it came together in that way."<ref name="M.I.A"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Chris|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/02/12/new-video-rihanna-rude-boy/|title=New Video: Rihanna, 'Rude Boy'|work=''MTV''|publisher=Viacom|date=2010-02-12|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The music video was nominated in the 'Best Editing' category at the [[2010 MTV Video Music Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/08/03/mtvs-vma-nominations-winners-and-losers/|title=MTV's VMA Nominations: Five surprise winners and losers|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]] division of [[Time Warner]]|date=2010-08-03|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> but lost to [[Lady Gaga]]'s "[[Bad Romance]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2010/best-editing/|title=Best Editing|work=''MTV''|publisher=Viacom|date=2010-09-20|accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref>

==Live performances==
To promote the song as the third single in the US, Rihanna performed "Rude Boy" for the first time live at the Pepsi Super Bowl Fan Jam on [[VH1]] in South Beach, Miami, on February 4, 2010.<ref name="RapUpSuperBowl">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/05/pepsi-super-bowl-fan-jam-rihanna-keri-hilson-jojo-timbaland-justin-bieber/|title=Pepsi Super Bowl Fan Jam: Rihanna, JoJo, Keri Hilson, Timbaland, & Justin Bieber|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-02-05|accessdate=2010-03-18}}</ref> Rihanna performed "Rude Boy" as part of a three-piece set list, which also included the previous singles from ''Rated R'', "Russian Roulette" and "Hard", the latter of which she was joined on stage by American rapper [[Young Jeezy]], who is featured on the song.<ref name="RapUpSuperBowl"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/pepsi_superbowl_2010/series.jhtml|title=Pepsi Super Bowl Fan Jam 2010|work=''[[VH1]]''|publisher=Viacom|accessdate=2010-03-18}}</ref> On February 2, 2010, Rihanna taped and performed a number of songs for "[[AOL]] Music Sessions", which were made available to view on the AOL website on February 23, 2010.<ref name="AOLSessions">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/24/video-rihanna-does-aol-music-sessions/|title=Video: Rihanna does 'AOL Music Sessions'|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-02-24|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Daw|first=Robbie|url=http://idolator.com/5420442/rihanna-belts-out-five-hits-for-aol-sessions|title=Rihanna Belts Out Five Hits For AOL Sessions|work=''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]''|publisher=[[Buzz Media]]|date=2010-02-24|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The set included Rihanna's most recent hit singles "Russian Roulette" and "Hard", as well as "[[Take a Bow (Rihanna song)|Take a Bow]]" and a stripped down version of "[[Disturbia (song)|Disturbia]]".<ref name="AOLSessions"/> She also performed the song on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', which aired on Presidents day on February 15, 2010, which featured Rihanna wearing black shorts and a leather visor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Daw|first=Robbie|url=http://idolator.com/5409062/rihanna-does-rude-boy-on-ellen|title=Rihanna Does <U+201C>Rude Boy<U+201D> On <U+2018>Ellen<U+2019>|work=''Idolator''|publisher=Buzz Media|date=2010-02-15|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/15/video-rihanna-gets-rude-on-ellen/|title=Rihanna gets rude on 'Ellen'|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-02-15|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>

As part of promotion in the United Kingdom, Rihanna appeared in a pre-recorded appearance on ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]'' on February 24, 2010, which aired the following day.<ref name="ChattyMan">{{cite web|last=Mcconnell|first=Donna|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1253666/Rihannas-solution-bad-hair-day-A-Nora-Batty-style-hairnet.html|title=Less chat, more action as  Rihanna gives Alan Carr a shock with her dance moves|work=''Mail Online''|publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust|date=2010-02-25|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> Rihanna appeared wearing a crop-top and shorts, a hairnet and large golden hooped earrings and also gave a demonstration of the various dance moves which are featured in the video during the interview.<ref name="ChattyMan"/> The song was also performed on [[GMTV]] the following day, where Rihanna wore a black dress with a open slit across her chest, with two arrows pointing towards her breasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/02/26/video-rihanna-brings-out-the-guns/|title=Rihanna brings out the guns|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-02-26|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> In Germany, Rihanna performed the song at the [[ECHO Awards]] in Berlin, Germany, on March 4, 2010.<ref name="EchoRapUp">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/03/04/rihanna-arrives-at-echo-awards-sets-billboard-record/|title=Rihanna arrives at Echo Awards, sets Billboard record|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-03-04|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The performance featured Rihanna on stage with two larger than life mechanical robots, which interacted with her throughout the performance.<ref>{{cite web|last=Daw|first=Robbie|url=http://idolator.com/5433662/rihanna-gets-lippy-with-a-robot-at-the-2010-echo-awards|title=Rihanna Gets Lippy With A Robot At The 2010 ECHO Awards|work=''Idolator''|publisher=Buzz Media|date=2010-03-05|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>

On March 27, 2010, Rihanna performed "Rude Boy" as part of a medley with "Hard" and "[[Don't Stop the Music (Rihanna song)|Don't Stop the Music]]" at the [[2010 Kids' Choice Awards|2010 Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]], held at UCLA<U+2019>s Pauley Pavilion in Westwood, California.<ref name="KidsChoice">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/03/27/rihanna-invades-kids-choice-awards/|title=Rihanna invades Kids' Choice Awards|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|date=2010-03-27|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The performance featured a large camouflage tank as well as two robots, similar to the performance at the ECHO Awards.<ref name="KidsChoice"/> On May 23, 2010, Rihanna performed a 40 minute set at [[BBC Radio 1]]'s Big Weekend Music Festival in Bangor, Wales.<ref name="Bigweekend">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1280659/Rihannas-Radio-1-Big-Weekend-leather-stage-outfit-steals-show.html|title=Rihanna's raunchy Big Weekend: Superstar steals the show with leather-clad performance|work=''Mail Online''|publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust|date=2010-05-24|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The performance featured Rihanna wearing a leather hooded playsuit with red, green and yellow stripes<ref name="Bigweekend"/> as she performed several of her biggest hits, which included "Mad House", "Hard", "Disturbia", "Rude Boy", "[[Te Amo (Rihanna song)|Te Amo]]", "Russian Roulette", "Don't Stop the Music", "[[SOS (Rihanna song)|SOS]]" and "[[Umbrella (song)|Umbrella]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend/2010/artists/rihanna/|title=Rihanna - Setlist|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The song was also featured on her [[Last Girl on Earth Tour]] (2009-10)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1267260/Rihanna-lights-Netherlands-dazzling-display--Belgian-fans-left-disappointed.html|title=Rihanna lights up the Netherlands with electrifying performance and SEVEN costume changes|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|date=2010-04-19|accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> as well as the current [[Loud Tour]] (2011).<ref>{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/07/rihanna-is-loud-sexy-and-larger-than-life|title=Rihanna is loud, sexy and larger than life|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|publisher=[[Sun Media]]|date=2011-06-07|accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref>

